Below is a **complete, self‑contained design** for an OCaml binding to a (hypothetical) C++ library *libpcapng* that offers an iterator over captured frames.  

The binding lets OCaml code do

```ocaml
let () =
  let p = Pcapng.open_file "sample.pcapng" in
  Pcapng.iter p (fun frame ->
      (* user code – one frame at a time *)
      Printf.printf "frame %Ld  %f s  %d bytes\n%!"
        (Int64.of_int frame.original_len) frame.timestamp
        frame.captured_len);
  Pcapng.close p
```

The design follows the **“push‑style”** pattern used by data‑frame libraries such as Polars or pandas: the C++ iterator drives the loop and calls back into OCaml for each element.  

---

## 1. The OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`)

```ocaml
(** pcapng.mli – public interface for the OCaml bindings *)

(** An opaque handle to a opened pcapng file / iterator. *)
type t

(** A single captured frame.  All fields are immutable. *)
type frame = {
  timestamp    : float;   (** seconds since epoch – as reported by the file *)
  captured_len : int;     (** number of bytes actually stored in the file *)
  original_len : int;     (** length of the original packet on the wire *)
  data         : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes, length = captured_len *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file.  Raises [Invalid_argument] if the file cannot be opened. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a previously opened file.  Idempotent – calling it twice is safe. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over *all* frames in the file, invoking the supplied OCaml callback
    for each frame.  The callback runs in the same thread as the C++ iterator.
    If the callback raises an exception, iteration stops and the exception is
    propagated to the caller.  The iterator is *eager* – the whole file is
    traversed before [iter] returns. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** A “lazy” version that returns the next frame on demand.
    Returns [None] when the file is exhausted. *)
val next : t -> frame option
```

### Design notes

* **`t`** is a custom block that contains a pointer to a C++ `PcapngReader`.  
  A finaliser automatically calls `close` when the OCaml value is GC‑collected,
  so users are not forced to call `close` (but it is recommended for deterministic
  resource release).

* **`frame`** is a plain OCaml record.  The C stub builds a fresh record for each
  frame, copying the packet bytes into a newly‑allocated `bytes`.  This keeps the
  OCaml view immutable and safe.

* **`iter`** is the main entry point that mirrors the “apply a function to each
  row” idiom of data‑frame libraries.  It is implemented in C: the C++ iterator
  walks the file and calls back into OCaml for each frame.  The callback may
  raise an exception; the stub catches it, aborts the C++ loop and re‑raises it
  on the OCaml side.

* **`next`** is a convenience “pull‑style” iterator for those who prefer explicit
  control.  It is built on top of the same C++ iterator object, but it does not
  use a callback – the stub returns a fresh OCaml value (or `None`) each time
  it is called.

